<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1931-03-01T08:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1931-03-01T08:00:00-05:00" n="989" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d989">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">823.00 Revolutions/119: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Peru</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Dearing</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Lima</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1931-03-01T08:00:00-05:00">March 1, 1931—8
                                a.m.</date><lb/>[Received 2:15 p.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>72. Juan O’Connor, chief of Flying Service, has seized two
                            Johnson-Shippee planes and ordered pilots Hay, Shippee and Johnson, over
                            their protest, to make a flight with military officers to Pisco. I am
                            protesting at once to Foreign Minister and asking release of planes and
                            pilots. Major Allen<note n="5" xml:id="d989fn5">Major C. J. Allen,
                                Military Attaché.</note> is doing the same to Juan.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Dearing</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>